analysis of the entire series. Focusing on the show’s depictions of the built environment of the city of Baltimore and the geographic dimensions of race and class, he analyzes how The Wire’s creator and showrunner, David Simon, uses the show to develop a social vision of its historical moment, as well as a device for critiquing many social “givens.” In The Wire’s gritty portrayals of drug dealers, cops, longshoremen, school officials and students, and members of the judicial system, Corkin maps a web of relationships and forces that define urban social life, and the lives of the urban underclass in particular, in the early twenty-first century. He makes a compelling case that, with its embedded history of race and race relations in the United States, The Wire is perhaps the most sustained and articulate exploration of urban life in contemporary popular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBaltimore (Md.)-Drama. 0aRace relations on television. 0aSocial classes on television. 0aTelevision programsxSocial aspects. 0aTelevision programszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aTelevision programs-Social aspects. 0aTelevision programs-United States-History and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31176940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477311783423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477311783/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK